Acordly.ai ACORD Form Decision Tree — Carrier-Grade Coverage Modeling
The AI should first identify each line of coverage or requirement present on the uploaded documents (especially the declarations page) and then suggest the matching ACORD forms. 
Overview: Upload → Form Matching (AI suggestions + preview SQS) → User Review/Confirm → Targeted Extraction & Mapping → Identity & Regulatory Checks + Cross-Form Validation → Definitive SQS → Submission Improvement Engine (loop) → Finalization.
In practice, ACORD 125 is always the foundational form for any commercial submission, and all other forms branch off based on specific exposures or requests on the dec page. Below we outline the decision criteria for each key ACORD form, with the triggers (what to look for) and how each form differs in purpose.
To ensure the decision tree operates at a true carrier-grade standard, the system must explicitly model the following underwriting expectations across applicable ACORD forms and validation layers:
* Property valuation method (Replacement Cost Value vs Actual Cash Value)
* Cause-specific deductibles (e.g., wind/hail, earthquake, flood, AOP)
* Coinsurance and agreed value logic
* Business Income and Extra Expense structure (limits and period of restoration)
* Commercial auto deductibles and physical damage valuation
* Auto liability limit structure (CSL vs split limits)
* Auto coverage symbols and scope alignment
* Optional auto coverages (UM/UIM, Med Pay/PIP, Hired & Non-Owned, Drive Other Car)
* Endorsements that materially affect limits, deductibles, or valuation economics
* State-specific regulatory and underwriting requirements
These elements are not optional enhancements or advanced features. They represent baseline underwriting expectations that materially affect pricing, eligibility, attachment, and claim outcomes.
Failure to model these dimensions does not merely reduce submission quality — it increases follow-up friction, misrepresents risk, and undermines underwriter confidence. Properly modeled, these inputs feed directly into cross-form validation, rejection prevention, and Submission Quality Score (SQS) accuracy.




Master Rule
Assumption: This a commercial insurance submission.
1. Identify document type(s)
   * Formats can be structured and/or unstructured including: PDF, DOC, XLS, CSV, JPEG, PNG, TIFF, RTF, ZIP
   * Uploads can include: Dec pages (current / expired), Quotes / proposals / indications, Schedules (vehicles, equipment, locations), Loss runs, Prior apps / supplements, Endorsement requests (AI, PNC, WOS, mortgagee, loss payee)
2. Choose the “primary truth set” for extraction (not every doc is equally authoritative)
Base Requirement: Use ACORD 125 as the anchor. (ACORD 125 is mandatory for every commercial submission.) 
* All other forms are selected and validated relative to the data in ACORD 125. 
* Identify policy period(s)
* Identify “current policy” vs “requested change” vs “historical”
Why it matters: Prevents the AI from pulling stale limits, wrong dates, or conflicting insured names from the wrong file.


________________




ACORD 125 — Commercial Insurance Application. Master application / cover sheet for the submission. It must exist before other forms. 
Full Context: The master application used for any new or renewed commercial account[1][2]. Trigger: If the uploaded documents indicate a new business submission or changes to existing coverage (any line), include ACORD 125. It captures core business info (ownership, revenues, operations, locations) and which lines of coverage are desired[1][3]. For example, if the dec page shows any insurance lines (GL, Property, Auto, WC, etc.), ACORD 125 should be present so underwriters have the full applicant profile. Difference: Unlike line-specific schedules, 125 provides a consistent overview for the entire risk[1][3]. Underwriters expect 125 as the first form; missing or inconsistent 125 data (e.g. revenue vs GL payroll mismatch) is a red flag
Triggers: Always required when user indicates commercial submission or dec page shows any of: GL, Property, Auto, WC, Umbrella, Inland Marine, Builders Risk, Cyber, Crime, Contractors work, Certificates requested. 
Document cues / OCR keywords: business name, NAICS/industry, owner names, locations, revenue, payroll, “lines of coverage”, policy effective dates, “certificate holder”, “mortgagee”.
Required variables to extract: legal name, DBA, entity type, FEIN (if present), primary address, mailing address, operations description by location, total revenue, total payroll, requested lines (Y/N per line), renewal/new indicator, prior carrier & loss run flag, Policy effective and expiration dates
Cross-form validations: All derived form values (payroll, revenue, locations, operations) become reconciliation anchors — other forms must match these values or provide an explicit explanation (ACORD 101). Validated fields include: Payroll totals, Revenue totals, Location counts, Operations descriptions, and Requested coverage lines.
Identity & Dates Integrity Checks: Underwriters expect absolute consistency in the insured’s identity and policy term. Failures here erode trust and create E&O exposure. The AI must enforce the following Identity & Dates validations:
* Named Insured Consistency
   * Legal named insured must match across:
      * ACORD 125
      * Dec page
      * All schedules and line-specific forms
   * DBAs must be consistently represented or explicitly explained
* FEIN Consistency
   * If FEIN is present, it must match across all documents where listed
   * Conflicting FEINs → hard stop
* Address Mapping
   * Physical locations must align between:
      * ACORD 125
      * Property schedules (140)
      * Other location-based forms
   * Mailing vs physical address distinctions must be explicit
* Effective / Expiration Dates
   * Policy periods must be consistent across:
      * ACORD 125
      * Dec page
      * All attached forms
   * Misaligned dates → hard stop unless explained
* Location Count Reconciliation
   * Number of locations must reconcile across:
      * ACORD 125
      * ACORD 140
      * Any attached schedules
   * Mismatches require explanation or correction
SQS effect: ACORD 125 completeness = structural completeness portion (25%) of SQS. Missing 125 → hard stop, SQS = 0 (or cap). 
Decision rule (pseudo):
* IF commercial_submission_detected THEN require ACORD_125
* IF ACORD_125 not provided THEN block submission (Implementation note:** OCR confidence threshold for key fields (business name, location) = 90%. If <90% for critical fields, surface to user for manual confirmation.


________________


ACORD 126 — Commercial General Liability
Full Context: Used whenever the risk has General Liability exposure[4]. Trigger: If the dec page or support docs list general liability coverage (limits for Premises/Operations, Products/Completed Ops, Personal/Advertising Injury, etc.) or reference GL premiums, then include ACORD 126. The AI should scan for keywords like “liability,” “premises-operations,” “products,” “bodily injury,” etc. What it does: ACORD 126 gathers details about GL exposures – business operations, locations, payroll/sales by class, subcontractors used, and past loss history[4]. For example, if a declarations page shows a GL limit or describes the insured’s operations (e.g. manufacturing, construction), the AI flags ACORD 126. Difference: This form drills into liability specifics (class codes, exposures, loss run details) that are not covered on ACORD 125[4]. Always attach 126 alongside 125 if GL is present, so that underwriting has the full exposure picture.
Purpose: Capture GL exposures, class codes, limits, operations, and claims info. 
Triggers: Dec page shows GL limits / GL premium / wording like “General Liability”, “Products/Completed Ops”, “Premises/Operations”, “Personal & Advertising Injury”.
Document cues / keywords: “GL”, “General Liability”, “BI”, “PD”, “Products/Completed”, class code numbers, payroll for clerical vs non-clerical, subcontractor language, Additional Insured requests.
Required variables to extract: GL limits, deductible, claim form (occurrence/claims-made), operations description, GL class codes, payroll or revenue used as exposure base, list of additional insureds.
Cross-form validations:
* GL class codes must align with operations in ACORD 125. If mismatch → require ACORD 101. 
* If business does construction work, ensure ACORD 186 is attached and % subcontracted reconciles with GL & WC fields.
SQS effect: GL completeness and class-code alignment = Exposure Consistency (25%). Missing GL class-code match = large negative weight; counts toward top risk drivers.
Decision rule (pseudo):
* IF dec_page.contains(GL_terms) OR 125.requested_line(GL) THEN add ACORD_126
* IF ACORD_126.class_codes do not align with 125.operations THEN flag for ACORD_101 and decrement SQS
Implementation note: If OCR finds numeric class codes, attempt automatic class-code normalization (strip punctuation, map to canonical list). If class code ambiguous, surface to user with confidence score.
Example hard/soft warnings:
* Hard stop? No — but require ACORD 101 if class-code/operation mismatch. Rejection risk increases substantially. 
Other: Risk transfer requirements detection (AI / PNC / WOS / endorsements) + workflow
Risk Transfer Requirements” module
Detect from contracts, COI requirements, lease language, and dec notes:
* Additional Insured required?
* Primary & Noncontributory required?
* Waiver of Subrogation required?
* Certificate holder / mortgagee / loss payee
* Specific wording requirements
Output should be:
* Not just “generate ACORD 25,” but also a compliance checklist for the broker (endorsements / wording requirements)
* This can feed SQS (because missing required risk-transfer language creates downstream failure)

