ACORD 127 — Business Auto
Full Context: Used for all Commercial Auto exposures[7]. Trigger: If the applicant has owned or leased vehicles (e.g. car/fleet limits on the dec page, or a schedule of autos), include ACORD 127. The AI should detect any list of vehicles (year/make/vin) or mention of auto liability/physical damage. What it does: ACORD 127 collects vehicle schedules, driver information, use of vehicles, and auto policy details[7]. For example, a dec page that shows a Business Auto liability limit or describes vehicles triggers the AI to add ACORD 127. Difference: This form is only for auto exposures. It standardizes vehicle data (who drives, radius of operation, Hired/Non-owned vehicles) in a structured way[7]. Without 127, key auto underwriting details would be missing.
Purpose: Vehicle schedules, driver exposures, radius of operation, auto limits, deductibles, and physical damage structure.
Triggers:
            * Dec page lists owned or leased vehicles
            * Auto liability limits present
            * “Business Auto” referenced
            * Vehicle schedule attached
            * “Hired Auto” or “Non-Owned Auto” mentioned
Document Cues / OCR Keywords: VINs, plate numbers, year/make/model, “Hired Auto”, “Non-Owned”, “Garage Operations”, driver names, driver age.
Required Variables to Extract
            * Vehicle schedule (VIN, year, make/model)
            * Garaging address(es)
            * Primary drivers
            * Business use and radius of operation
            * Liability limit structure (CSL vs split)
            * Physical damage valuation (ACV vs Agreed/Stated Value)
            * Comprehensive and collision deductibles
Cross-Form Validations
            * If GL includes Hired / Non-Owned exposure, ensure ACORD 127 contains corresponding auto data (do not rely on GL alone).
            * If Umbrella coverage is requested (ACORD 131), underlying Auto limits must meet umbrella attachment requirements.
            * Auto policy period should align with umbrella period when umbrella attaches to auto.
Coverage Integrity Checks
            * Liability limits:
            * If split limits are selected, all components (BI per person, BI per accident, PD per accident) must be present.
            * Incomplete liability structure → hard stop.
            * Physical damage:
            * If physical damage is present, comp and collision deductibles are required.
            * If Agreed Value or Stated Amount is selected, vehicle schedule confirmation is required.
            * Coverage symbols:
            * Symbols must align with exposure (e.g., hired/non-owned symbols present when exposure exists).
            * Physical damage symbols must align with scheduled autos.
SQS Effect
            * Missing vehicle schedule or driver list → moderate SQS penalty.
            * Auto limits shown without vehicle detail → soft warning; may escalate to hard stop if umbrella minimums apply.
            * Deductibles, limit structure, and symbols clearly defined → neutral to positive SQS impact.
            * Symbol mismatch or incomplete limits → negative SQS impact.
Decision Rule (Pseudo)
            * IF dec_page.contains(vehicle_terms OR auto_limits) OR ACORD 125.requested_line(Auto) → add ACORD 127
            * IF umbrella_requested AND auto_limits < umbrella_minimum → hard stop
Implementation Note: For fleet submissions, require at least 80% OCR confidence on VIN and vehicle year before auto-filling schedules; otherwise prompt for a vehicle schedule upload.
Optional Coverage Detection (Advisory)
            * Medical Payments / PIP (state-dependent)
            * Uninsured / Underinsured Motorist (BI / PD)
            * Hired & Non-Owned Auto Liability
            * Drive Other Car
If optional coverages are listed, extract limits. If exposure exists but coverage is omitted, surface an advisory warning only (no auto-add).


________________


ACORD 131 — Umbrella / Excess Liability
Full Context: Used when an umbrella or excess policy is requested[8]. Trigger: If the dec page shows an umbrella/excess limit (above the primary GL/Auto limit) or notes “excess liability,” include ACORD 131. The AI should notice any mention of an umbrella layer or excess coverage. What it does: ACORD 131 records umbrella/excess limits and attachment points, and it schedules the underlying primary policies (GL, Auto, etc.) that back the umbrella[8][9]. For instance, a dec page listing “Umbrella Liability – $2M” means 131 is needed. Difference: This form supplements ACORD 126/127: it ties together the upper layer with the underlying GL/Auto policies. It ensures the AI records how the umbrella attaches to primary limits and any self-insured retentions. In short, use 131 whenever excess limits appear on the dec page.
Purpose: Capture umbrella/excess policies and confirm underlying coverage. 
Triggers: Dec page lists Umbrella or “Excess Liability” or limits above primary GL/Auto.
Document cues / keywords: “Umbrella”, “Excess”, “attachment point”, “self-insured retention”, listed underlying policy numbers.
Required variables to extract: Umbrella limit, SIR, attachment points, list of underlying policies + limits, employers liability limits.
**Cross-form validation verify GL/Auto limits meet umbrella minimums. If not → hard stop (umbrella cannot attach without required underlying). 
Coverage Integrity Checks:
Carriers expect the entire liability stack to be internally consistent, not just adequately limited. The AI must enforce the following:
            * GL Form Consistency
            * If GL is claims-made, require:
            * Retro date
            * Prior acts confirmation
            * Flag missing retro/prior acts as a coverage integrity issue
            * Deductible / SIR Consistency
            * Validate deductibles and SIRs are consistent across:
            * ACORD 126 / 127
            * ACORD 131
            * Dec page representations
            * Flag unexplained discrepancies
            * Policy Period Alignment
            * Underlying GL, Auto, and WC policy periods must align with the umbrella policy period
            * Misaligned periods → coverage integrity warning or block, depending on workflow
            * WC Employers Liability Validation
            * If umbrella attaches over WC:
            * Confirm Employers Liability limits are present and meet minimums
            * Flag missing EL limits as attachment failure risk
SQS effect: Umbrella adequacy influences Umbrella & Limit Adequacy (10%). Failed attachment → hard stop or severe SQS cap. Coverage integrity issues → SQS penalties and increased underwriter follow-up risk.
Decision rule (pseudo):
            * IF dec_page.contains(Umbrella_terms) OR 125.requested_line(Umbrella) THEN add ACORD_131
            * IF underlying_limits < umbrella_minimum THEN block_or_require_explanation
Implementation note: When underlying policies are detected, attempt automatic matching by policy number, effective dates, and limits; if matching confidence is insufficient, require ACORD 101.






________________


ACORD 140 — Commercial Property
Full Context: Used for commercial property coverages[10]. Trigger: If the dec page includes Property insurance (buildings, contents, equipment) – e.g. any covered locations with insured values – include ACORD 140. The AI should detect addresses, building values, business personal property (BPP) limits, or occupancy details. What it does: ACORD 140 captures each insured location in detail: addresses, construction type, occupancy, protection features, roof year, valuation basis, and itemized values[11]. For example, if a dec page lists a building value or COPE details, ACORD 140 is required. Difference: This form replaces a freeform property schedule; it standardizes property COPE data that isn’t in 125. It tells underwriters exactly what is insured at each location (e.g. steel frame, concrete block, sprinklered)[10]. Without 140, the insurer won’t have the physical structure details.
Purpose: COPE (Construction, Occupancy, Protection, Exposure) and per-location values for fixed property. 
Triggers: Dec page lists buildings, building values, BPP, location addresses or property premiums.
Document cues / keywords: “Building limit”, “BPP”, address lines, construction type, sprinklered, roof year, “business income” attachment.
Required variables to extract: Address(es), construction type, occupancy, protection class/fire protection details, year built/roof year, building value, BPP value, business income values and period of restoration details.
Cross-form validations:
            * If Builders Risk present (ACORD 133), values should not double-count with ACORD 140. Prevent duplication. 
            * If inland-marine also present, ensure scheduled items aren’t counted twice under property. (140 vs 160)
SQS effect: Property COPE completeness = Property Integrity (15%). Missing COPE fields → hard stop for many carriers (policy requires full COPE).
Decision rule (pseudo):
            * IF dec_page.contains(building_terms OR property_values) OR 125.requested_line(Property) THEN add ACORD_140
            * IF COPE fields incomplete THEN block submission (Implementation note:** Property data must be location-specific; require OCR confidence and/or manual confirmation for each address. If business income requested but no values present, de-rate SQS and prompt for ACORD 810/811 attachments.
Defining “minimum viable COPE” vs “carrier-grade COPE”:
Minimum Viable COPE: (Required to submit without hard stop)
This is the absolute minimum information most carriers need to accept a commercial property submission into underwriting. If any of these are missing, the submission should be blocked.
Required Fields — Per Location:
            * Street address (full physical location)
            * Occupancy type (what the building is used for)
            * Construction type (broad category)
            * Total building value (if building coverage requested)
            * BPP value (if contents coverage requested)
Acceptable Granularity:
            * Construction:
            * “Frame” / “Joisted masonry” / “Non-combustible” / “Masonry non-combustible”
            * Occupancy:
            * Office / Retail / Warehouse / Manufacturing / Contractor yard
Explicitly Not Required at this tier:
            * Roof year
            * Sprinkler details
            * Fire protection class
            * Business income details
            * Valuation method (RC/ACV) if value present
Rule: Minimum Viable COPE = enough information for an underwriter to identify what is insured, where it is, and its basic risk class.
System Behavior:
            * Missing any minimum field → HARD STOP
            * All minimum fields present → allow submission, but cap SQS
Carrier-Grade COPE (Required for SQS ≥ 90 and “Carrier-Ready” status)
This is the level of detail carriers expect for fast quotes, clean binds, and no follow-ups. Missing items here do not block submission, but they meaningfully reduce SQS.
Required Fields — Per Location: Everything in Minimum Viable COPE, plus:
            * Year built
            * Roof year
            * Sprinklered (Y/N + type if available)
            * Fire protection details
            * Distance to fire hydrant
            * Fire department type (volunteer / professional)
            * Protection class (if known)
            * Valuation method (RC vs ACV)
            * Business income values
            * BI limit
            * Period of restoration
Optional (Bonus / Differentiators)
            * Square footage
            * Alarm systems
            * Flood zone (if known)
            * Prior property losses by location
Rule: Carrier-Grade COPE = enough information for underwriting to price the risk without follow-up.
System Behavior:
            * Missing carrier-grade fields → SQS penalties only
            * No hard stops unless carrier-specific rules apply
Adjusted SQS Mapping - Property Integrity (15% total)
COPE Tier
	Max Property Integrity Score
	Missing Minimum
	0% (hard stop)
	Minimum Viable Only
	~60–70%
	Carrier-Grade
	100%
	Overall SQS Impact:
            * Minimum Viable COPE caps overall SQS at ~85
            * Carrier-Grade COPE required for 90+ Carrier-Ready


