ACORD 141 — Property Schedule (Scheduled Items)
Full Context: Used when scheduling specific property items. Trigger: If the property being insured includes high-value or special items that need separate schedules (e.g. equipment floaters, fine arts, scheduled property), the AI should use ACORD 141 to list them. The dec page might simply say “See attached schedule” or list scheduled items (e.g. computer equipment, jewelry, contractor’s equipment). What it does: ACORD 141 allows detailed scheduling of covered items by location or category. It often supplements ACORD 140 by itemizing contents or specific property. Difference: This form is essentially an add-on to the property section. If a location has scheduled property beyond the basic building/BPP (for instance, expensive computers or a contractor’s tool schedule), the AI should attach ACORD 141. (Without 141, these values would not appear on the primary forms.)
Purpose: Capture COPE (Construction, Occupancy, Protection, Exposure) and per-location property values, plus property-specific underwriting attributes (valuation method, deductibles, coinsurance, BI/EE) required for accurate rating, attachment checks, and carrier submission readiness.
Triggers
            * Dec page lists building values, BPP, property premiums, or location addresses
            * User requests property coverage or attachments (BI, schedules)
            * Any reference to “building limit”, “business personal property”, “property schedule”, or lender/mortgagee instructions
Document cues / OCR keywords: “Building limit”, “BPP”, address lines, construction type, sprinklered, roof year, “business income”, “RCV”, “ACV”, “deductible”, “coinsurance”, “agreed value”, “period of restoration”, peril-specific deductibles (wind/hail, flood, earthquake).
Required variables to extract (per location)
Standard COPE & values:
            * Street address (full physical location)
            * Construction type (broad category)
            * Occupancy type (use)
            * Protection features (sprinkler Y/N + type if available)
            * Protection class / distance to hydrant / fire department type
            * Year built / roof year
            * Building insured value (limit)
            * Business Personal Property (BPP) value
            * Valuation basis (RCV vs ACV) 
            * Business income (BI) values: BI limit, period of restoration 
            * Extra Expense limit (if applicable) 
Property financial & coverage mechanics:
            * Deductible structure: AOP deductible, wind/hail deductible, earthquake deductible, flood deductible, deductible basis (flat dollar or percentage), deductible application (per occurrence, per cause)
            * Coinsurance percentage or agreed value endorsement indicator
            * Underlying mortgagee/lender names and mortgagee clause if present
Coverage tower & consistency items:
            * Underlying policy overlap indicators (Builders Risk, Inland Marine references)
            * Location-specific prior property losses (optional but valuable)
            * Policy effective/expiration dates (for period alignment)
Cross-form validations & coverage-integrity checks (expanded)
            * COPE duplication prevention: If Builders Risk (ACORD 133) present, ensure construction-period values do not duplicate ACORD 140 completed-property values. If Inland Marine (ACORD 160) present, ensure scheduled mobile items are not double-counted in 140/141.
            * Valuation consistency: RCV values must be consistent with replacement-cost intent (higher insured amounts, new-construction cost indicators). ACV selection with high insured limits or recent construction must be flagged for confirmation.
            * Deductible consistency: Deductible structures must be sensible for geography (e.g., wind/hail expected in coastal zones). Peril-specific deductibles present on the dec page must be defined in the submission.
            * Coinsurance / agreed value: If a coinsurance clause applies, ensure coinsurance percentage or an agreed-value endorsement is provided or triggered.
            * Business Income alignment: BI limit and period of restoration must be present if BI coverage requested; cross-check for values in dec page and BI attachments.
            * Location counts and mapping: Location counts and addresses must reconcile with ACORD 125 locations and any schedules (ACORD 141). Mismatches → explanation required.
            * Policy dates alignment: Ensure effective/expiration dates for property coverage align with overall policy period and any umbrella/underlying periods where relevant.
Decision rules (pseudo + actionable)
            1. Base inclusion
            * IF dec_page.contains(building_terms OR property_values) OR 125.requested_line(Property) THEN add ACORD_140.
            2. Minimum Viable COPE enforcement
            * IF any Minimum_Viable_COPE field missing (street address, occupancy, construction, building value when requested, BPP when requested) → HARD STOP.
            3. Carrier-Grade COPE / SQS gating
            * IF only Minimum_Viable_COPE present THEN allow submission but cap SQS (see SQS mapping). Prompt user to supply Carrier-Grade COPE fields.
            4. Valuation method
            * IF property_coverage_detected THEN attempt to extract valuation method (RCV or ACV).
            * IF valuation method missing → SOFT BLOCK (prompt user for selection); de-rate SQS.
            * IF RCV selected → validate that building/BPP values are consistent with replacement cost intent.
            * IF ACV selected → allow submission but flag for depreciation exposure and SQS adjustments.
            5. Deductible structure
            * IF property values present THEN require deductible information by peril (AOP default plus wind/hail, earthquake, flood where applicable).
            * IF peril-specific deductible referenced but undefined → HARD STOP.
            * IF deductibles absent but geography expects them (e.g., wind/hail zone) → allow submission but cap SQS.
            6. Coinsurance
            * IF coinsurance clause applies → require coinsurance percentage or agreed value confirmation.
            * IF coinsurance applies but value is missing → SOFT BLOCK and prompt user.
            7. Business Income (BI)
            * IF BI coverage requested → require BI limit and period of restoration.
            * IF BI limit present but period missing → SOFT BLOCK.
            8. Duplication & stack checks
            * IF Builders Risk or Inland Marine references exist → dedupe values, require explanation or schedule mapping.
            9. Final validation
            * After form selection and field extraction → run cross-form validations (dates, location counts, valuation vs values, deductibles, coinsurance, BI completeness). If any hard-stop condition triggered → block submission; otherwise compute SQS and present remediation steps.
COPE Tiering (Minimum Viable vs Carrier-Grade) — summary (keeps prior definitions)
            * Minimum Viable COPE (HARD STOP if missing) — address, occupancy, construction, building value (if requested), BPP (if requested). Passing Minimum Viable allows submission but caps SQS.
            * Carrier-Grade COPE (needed for SQS ≥ 90) — Minimum Viable plus year built, roof year, sprinkler and fire protection details, protection class, valuation method (RCV/ACV), BI limit & period, deductible and coinsurance details. Missing Carrier-Grade fields → SQS penalties (not hard stops unless carrier-specific).
SQS mapping — Property Integrity (15% of SQS)
            * Missing Minimum Viable COPE → 0% (hard stop)
            * Minimum Viable only → ~60–70% for Property Integrity component
            * Carrier-Grade COPE → 100% for Property Integrity component
Additional SQS effects (examples):
            * Valuation method missing → negative SQS delta
            * RCV selected but values inconsistent → negative SQS delta
            * Missing peril-specific deductible where expected → negative SQS delta
            * Coinsurance unclear/missing → negative SQS delta
            * BI missing period of restoration → negative SQS delta
Overall SQS cap behavior:
            * Minimum Viable COPE present but Carrier-Grade missing → cap overall SQS ≈ 85
            * Carrier-Grade COPE present → SQS can reach 90+ (if other components meet thresholds)
Implementation notes: Property data must be location-specific; require OCR confidence thresholds (e.g., ≥90% for address and values, ≥80% for construction/occupancy) and surface ambiguous fields for manual confirmation; if BI or valuation fields are missing, prompt for ACORD 810/811 attachments or a user confirmation.
UI / UX prompts
            * If Minimum Viable COPE missing: “We need the physical address, occupancy, construction type, and the building or contents value to submit this property to underwriting.” (Block)
            * If Valuation method missing: “Select coverage valuation: Replacement Cost Value (RCV) or Actual Cash Value (ACV).” (Soft block / prompt)
            * If peril deductibles referenced but undefined: “Please specify deductible amounts and basis for wind/hail, flood, and earthquake per location.” (Hard stop)
            * If BI requested but missing period: “Please provide Period of Restoration for Business Income.” (Soft block / prompt)
Why this is necessary: Valuation, deductibles, coinsurance, and BI materially affect pricing, limits adequacy, and claims outcome. Making these fields first-class in ACORD 140 extraction and validation reduces underwriter follow-ups, improves SQS accuracy, and prevents E&O exposure from mispriced or misrepresented property risks.

________________


ACORD 133 — Builders Risk
Full Context: Used for builder’s risk projects. Trigger: If the submission involves property under construction (e.g. new building being erected or major renovation), include ACORD 133. The AI should check if the dec page or construction details mention “builder’s risk,” project cost, or completion date. What it does: ACORD 133 collects information specific to construction: project description, location, anticipated completion, values during construction, and how coverage is to be written (ground-up or renovation) for the structure-in-progress. Difference: This form is only relevant to construction projects. It differs from ACORD 140 (completed property) by covering the incomplete building. If a declaration has a section for builders risk (or the user tags it), the AI suggests ACORD 133 to capture those details.
Purpose: Covers property under construction / renovation — separate underwriting logic from 140.
Triggers: Dec page mentions “builders risk”, project name, project value, completion date, or a construction lender/mortgagee.
Document cues / keywords: “Under construction”, “renovation”, “project value”, “completion date”.
Required variables to extract: Project address, project cost, anticipated completion date, construction type, owner/contractor information, insured interest.
Cross-form validations: If both 133 and 140 exist for same location, ensure period covered is disjoint (one for construction period, the other for completed property). Prevent duplicate insured values.
SQS effect: Builders Risk missing critical project values/COPE = SQS penalty and possible hard stop.
Decision rule (pseudo):
            * IF dec_page.contains(construction_terms) OR 125.operations.contains(construction) THEN add ACORD_133
            * IF project_value_missing THEN block (HARD STOP) or require ACORD_101 with explanation


________________


ACORD 160 — Inland Marine
Full Context: Used for inland marine (floater) coverages. Trigger: If the insured has mobile property or transportation exposures (e.g. motor truck cargo, contractors’ equipment, equipment breakdown, accounts receivable floaters, etc.), include ACORD 160. The AI should notice any mention of “floater,” “marine,” “transit,” or classes like “equipment,” “value of construction equipment,” etc. What it does: ACORD 160 standardizes inland marine exposures: it collects descriptions and values of items that move or have special risks (including computer equipment, musical instruments, shipments, etc.). Difference: Unlike 140 (fixed property), 160 deals with movable property. If the policy includes inland marine coverage, 160 gives the underwriter a schedule of that property. For example, a dec page line “Inland Marine – Contractor’s Equipment” triggers ACORD 160 to list out the equipment details.
Purpose: Schedule floaters/moveable property (contractor’s equipment, cargo, instruments). 
Triggers: Dec page lists equipment in transit, contractor’s equipment, motor truck cargo, or explicitly “inland marine”.
Document cues / keywords: “Floater”, “inland marine”, “contractor’s equipment”, “cargo”, serial numbers.
Required variables to extract: Item descriptions, values, transit exposures, schedule durations.
Cross-form validations: Ensure items on 160 are not double-counted on 140/141/133.
SQS effect: Missing inland marine for obvious mobile exposures → moderate SQS deduction.
Decision rule (pseudo):
            * IF dec_page.contains(mobile_property_terms) THEN add ACORD_160
            * IF item appears in 140 or 141 THEN dedupe or require ACORD_101


________________


ACORD 186 — Contractors Supplemental
Full Context: Used for contracting operations. Trigger: If the insured is a contractor (especially in construction trades) and has contractor-related questions on the application or supplements (as indicated on the dec page or questionnaire), include ACORD 186. The AI should identify contractor-specific details: percent of work in renovation vs new, licensing, subcontracting practices, etc. What it does: ACORD 186 supplements the GL (126) with deep contractor info: type of contractor (GC, electrical, plumbing, etc.), work done (residential vs commercial, percent subcontracted), specialized exposures (e.g. blasting, demolition, scaffolding). Difference: This form is only used for contractors and fleshes out details that 125/126 don’t cover. If the dec page or attachments show a construction business, 186 is needed to convey their operational risks (e.g. any roofing work done, use of cranes, etc.).
Purpose: Add contractor-specific operational detail to support GL & WC. 
Triggers: 125.operations indicate construction trades or dec page lists contractor business.
Document cues / keywords: “Contractor”, “subcontractor”, “licensed”, percentage subcontracted, roofing, demolition, blasting, scaffolding.
Required variables to extract: Type of contractor, % subcontracted, residential vs commercial split, high-hazard operations, licensing details.
Cross-form validations: Subcontracting % must feed back into WC and GL exposures. High subcontracting with low WC payroll = red flag.
SQS effect: Missing 186 for contractor exposures → big SQS hit and higher pick of declination.
Decision rule (pseudo):
            * IF 125.operations.contains(contracting) THEN add ACORD_186
            * IF %subcontracted_conflict_with_WC_payroll THEN require ACORD_101 and/or COI collection workflow


________________


ACORD 137 — Crime
Full Context: Used for crime/employee dishonesty coverage. Trigger: If the dec page or supporting materials indicate a crime or fidelity policy (e.g. coverage for theft, forgery, employee dishonesty, ERISA bonds), include ACORD 137. The AI should watch for terms like “crime,” “money and securities,” “employee dishonesty,” etc. What it does: ACORD 137 captures coverages under a commercial crime policy (burglaries, robberies, employee theft, forgery, money orders, etc.), including limits and deductibles for each sub-limit. Difference: This is a highly specialized form. It supplements the core forms by detailing the various insuring agreements of a crime policy. If a declaration shows any crime coverage, the AI will suggest 137 to ensure all sections (parts A–E of crime coverage) are filled out.
Purpose: Employee dishonesty, money & securities, ERISA bonds.
Triggers: Dec page shows crime coverage, financial exposures, cashier/collections, or ERISA fiduciary mentions.
Document cues / keywords: “Crime”, “employee dishonesty”, “money and securities”, “forgery”.
Required variables: Limits by insuring agreement, deductible, locations, employee counts.
Cross-form validations: If company has high internal cash handling but no crime coverage → flag silent exposure (soft warning).
SQS effect: Absence of crime coverage when exposure exists → soft warning, reduced SQS.


________________


ACORD 138 — Cyber / Network Security
Full Context: Used for cyber liability coverage. Trigger: If cyber insurance is requested or present (e.g. “Cyber Liability,” “Data Breach,” “Network Security”), include ACORD 138. The AI should detect any mention of first- or third-party cyber coverage in the dec page or submission. What it does: ACORD 138 collects cyber risk details: types of digital assets insured, network security measures, prior breaches, and limits. Difference: This form is specific to cyber exposures. It supplements the core application with cyber-specific questions (like triggers for breach response). In other words, if the dec page or questions indicate cyber coverage is needed, 138 is the form to record that information.
Purpose: Cyber liability coverages: breach response, network security.
Triggers: Dec page requests cyber coverage or business handles PHI/PCI/e-commerce.
Document cues / keywords: “Cyber”, “Network Security”, “Data breach”, “PCI”, “PHI”, vendor/cloud use.
Required variables: Limits, prior incidents, controls in place (MFA, backups), third-party vendor exposures.
Cross-form validations: If business stores PHI/PCI and no cyber limits listed → soft-warning (recommend adding coverage).
SQS effect: Missing cyber for clear cyber exposure → SQS reduction (recommendation, not block).


________________


ACORD 25 & ACORD 28 — Certificates / Evidence
Full Context (25): Used when proof of liability coverage is needed (to a third party)[12]. Trigger: If the user indicates they need a certificate (e.g. to comply with a contract or lease) for GL, Auto, WC, or Umbrella coverage, include ACORD 25. The AI can spot this if the uploaded docs mention a “certificate holder” or require evidence of GL/Auto/WC insurance. What it is: ACORD 25 is a one-page Certificate of Liability Insurance that summarizes existing liability policies[12]. It lists policy numbers, limits, dates, and additional insureds in a compact format. For instance, if the dec page includes a section for “Certificate Holder,” or if a supporting letter asks “provide certificate,” the AI should generate ACORD 25. Difference: Unlike an application (125) or evidence form (28), ACORD 25 is purely informational. It does not collect new data; it reports that the insured already has liability coverage (GL, auto, umbrella, WC)[12][13]. It’s used by third parties (clients, landlords, lenders) to verify coverage exists.
Full Context (28): Used when proof of property coverage is needed[14]. Trigger: If a lender, landlord or other party requests evidence of the property policy (e.g. on a mortgage or lease), include ACORD 28. The AI should detect requests like “evidence of insurance” or a template for mortgagee notification. What it is: ACORD 28 provides a standardized one-page Evidence of Commercial Property Insurance. It functions like a COI but for property, listing the covered locations, covered property types, and mortgagee/loss payees[14]. For example, [Insureon] notes that if you rent business property, the landlord may require an ACORD 28 form as proof of coverage[14]. Difference: ACORD 28 is exclusively for property (the dec page’s buildings and BPP). Unlike 25 (liability) or 125 (application), it doesn’t add coverage; it certifies the existing property insurance to interested parties.
Purpose: Certificates (25) and property evidence (28) are proof-only documents for third parties (landlords, lenders). They do not replace application forms. 
Triggers: Supporting docs ask “provide certificate” or dec page includes “certificate holder / mortgagee” fields.
Document cues / keywords: “Certificate of Liability Insurance”, “Certificate Holder”, “Lender”, “Mortgagee”.
Required variables: Policy numbers, effective/expiration dates, limits, names of certificate holders or mortgagees.
SQS effect: Missing certificate when requested = user-facing failure (but not an underwriting hard stop. Prompt user to generate ACORD 25/28 post-bind.


________________


ACORD 101 — Additional Remarks Schedule
Full Context: Used whenever extra explanations or narrative are needed[15]. Trigger: Any time information won’t fit in the standard fields of a form, the AI should add ACORD 101. For example, if the dec page has a handwritten note, clarification of “yes” answers, ownership details, or any supplemental story (claims explanation, project descriptions), ACORD 101 is used. What it does: ACORD 101 is simply a free-text attachment (“Additional Remarks Schedule”) that can be appended to any other form[15]. Difference: It is not a standalone application. Instead, it provides overflow space – for instance, to describe operations not captured elsewhere, clarify affiliations, or answer underwriting questions in detail[15]. Whenever the AI detects that the uploaded documents contain miscellaneous notes or require narrative answers (or if an underwriter specifically needs more space), 101 should be attached.
Purpose: Narrative and clarifications — claims explanations, dec page inconsistencies, “yes” answers needing context. 
Triggers: Any inconsistency: payroll vs revenue mismatch, class-code conflicts, claims/exposure misalignment, or hand-written notes.
Document cues / keywords: “explain”, “note”, “see attached”, handwritten remarks, inconsistent numbers.
Required variables: Free-text narrative tied to the form(s) it supplements.
SQS effect: Good-quality narrative can repair SQS deficits (Narrative Quality = 10%). Poor or missing narratives when required increase declination risk.
Decision rule (pseudo):*
            * IF cross_form_conflict OR missing_explanation THEN require ACORD_101 before submission


Submission Quality Score (SQS™) — Implementation
Purpose: Predict quote speed, bind probability, and underwriter confidence prior to carrier submission. Use it to prioritize remediation work and to gate quality. 
Score range & tiers:
            * 90–100 Carrier-Ready (green)
            * 75–89 Review-Ready (yellow/green)
            * 60–74 At-Risk (yellow)
            * <60 Decline-Prone (red)
Hard-stop failures cap the score at 60. 
Weighted components (suggested implementation):**
               * Structural Completeness — 25% (ACORD 125 + required line forms present)
               * Exposure Consistency — 25% (class code & payroll alignment)
               * Property Integrity — 15% (COPE completeness)
               * Lost History Alignment — 15% (claims vs exposures)
               * Umbrella & Limit Adequacy — 10% (underlying limits vs umbrella)
               * Narrative Quality — 10% (ACORD 101 clarity)
SQS outputs to show the user: numeric SQS, top 3 risk drivers, and actionable steps (exact fields to complete or correct).
Algorithm notes: Implement as deterministic rule scoring with negative/positive deltas for each check, not as a black-box ML model at first. You can add ML later for predictive declination scoring.